From: Kamil Bienkiewicz <perceivalpercy@gmail.com>
Date: Sun, 24 May 2026 12:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] clk: qcom: nsscc-ipq5332: dedicated PPE freq_tbl + drop
 CLK_SET_RATE_PARENT

PPE_CLK_SRC currently shares ftbl_nss_cc_ce_clk_src which was copied
from the IPQ5424 driver and lies about the rates produced on this SoC:

    F(375000000, P_CMN_PLL_NSS_200M_CLK, 1, 0, 0)

On IPQ5424 the matching CMN PLL tap really outputs 375 MHz. On IPQ5332
the CMN PLL only emits 200 MHz from this tap (verified live: nss-200mhz
is registered at 200000000 Hz in clk_summary), so the entry describes
an unreachable rate.

Combined with CLK_SET_RATE_PARENT on the RCG, this broke every
clk_set_rate() call from the PPE driver:

  1. ppe.c calls clk_set_rate(ppe, 353000000)
  2. _freq_tbl_determine_rate() picks the F(375M, ...) entry via CEIL
  3. With CLK_SET_RATE_PARENT, the framework asks the parent
     (nss-200mhz, a fixed-rate clock) to produce 375 MHz
  4. clk_calc_new_rates() on a fixed-rate clock with no further parent
     returns NULL
  5. clk_core_set_rate_nolock() reports -EINVAL to the caller

Observed live on Flint 3 (boot dmesg):
  qcom_ppe 3a000000.ethernet: clk_set_rate(ppe, 353000000) failed: -22,
                              using current rate 24000000

The whole PPE clock subtree is then stuck at 24 MHz (XO), causing
~95% packet loss under sustained LAN traffic (PPE engine starved).

Fix:

  * Give PPE_CLK_SRC its own freq_tbl with rates the IPQ5332 CMN PLL
    can actually deliver: 24 MHz (XO), 200 MHz (NSS_200M), 300 MHz
    (NSS_300M).
  * Drop CLK_SET_RATE_PARENT from PPE_CLK_SRC so the framework no
    longer tries to retune the fixed parent.

With CEIL semantics, the PPE driver's clk_set_rate(353M) now lands
on the 300 MHz entry (the last one matched when no exact ceiling
exists) — the highest the IPQ5332 CMN PLL can deliver to the PPE.

CE_CLK_SRC and EIP_BFDCD_CLK_SRC still share the original (wrong) table
but no consumer calls clk_set_rate() on them today, so the bug is
inert there. U-Boot leaves CE at GPLL0/1 = 800 MHz which Linux reads
back via recalc_rate without consulting the table.

Signed-off-by: Kamil Bienkiewicz <perceivalpercy@gmail.com>
---
--- a/drivers/clk/qcom/nsscc-ipq5332.c
+++ b/drivers/clk/qcom/nsscc-ipq5332.c
@@ -558,17 +558,28 @@ static struct clk_rcg2 nss_cc_port3_tx_clk_src = {
 	},
 };

+/*
+ * IPQ5332 CMN PLL only provides 200 and 300 MHz NSS reference taps —
+ * a dedicated table avoids inheriting ftbl_nss_cc_ce_clk_src's bogus
+ * 375 MHz / NSS_200M entry copied from the IPQ5424 driver.
+ */
+static const struct freq_tbl ftbl_nss_cc_ppe_clk_src[] = {
+	F(24000000,  P_CMN_PLL_XO_CLK,       1, 0, 0),
+	F(200000000, P_CMN_PLL_NSS_200M_CLK, 1, 0, 0),
+	F(300000000, P_CMN_PLL_NSS_300M_CLK, 1, 0, 0),
+	{ }
+};
+
 static struct clk_rcg2 nss_cc_ppe_clk_src = {
 	.cmd_rcgr = 0x3ec,
 	.mnd_width = 0,
 	.hid_width = 5,
 	.parent_map = nss_cc_parent_map_0,
-	.freq_tbl = ftbl_nss_cc_ce_clk_src,
+	.freq_tbl = ftbl_nss_cc_ppe_clk_src,
 	.clkr.hw.init = &(const struct clk_init_data){
 		.name = "nss_cc_ppe_clk_src",
 		.parent_data = nss_cc_parent_data_0,
 		.num_parents = ARRAY_SIZE(nss_cc_parent_data_0),
-		.flags = CLK_SET_RATE_PARENT,
 		.ops = &clk_rcg2_ops,
 	},
 };
